LogFile.Subject: A8
LogFile.FinalText:
Coffee tasters have an easy time identifying quality coffee, but assigning an exact figure to each sample is an entirely different story. Coffee tasting is a skill developed with experience. However, the evaluations given by tasters are far from being exact, which makes it difficult to carry out large-scale evaluations. But coffee enthusiasts, do not despair: The online news published by Fapesp (a research funding agency for the state of São Paulo) reports on a promising product developed by Brazilian researchers, an "electronic tongue," a device that evaluates flavors much more precisely than the human tongue.
The human tongue is composed of sensory receptors called taste buds, which are responsible for the identification of flavor. Cientists at Embrapa (a Brazilian agriculture research agency) have developed a taste sensor that is much more sensitive than human buds when it comes to identifying the subtleties of flavor and the impurities found in beverages. The researchers were able to model human palate and develop microelectrodes covered by a small film composed of conducting polymers that generate a specific electric response for each substance. Different from human tasters, when the device identifies flavors that correspond to a flavor that has been previously registered, it generates a precise numerical evaluation even in the case of mixtures or flavor combinations.
